<p>
i saw this tiny old lady at the mall wearing a heathered grey sweatsuit with
‘new york’ embroidered in pink on the hood. if she and I were the only people
at the mall, I probably would’ve snapped a sneaky picture, but as it was busy
I wished in my head that I had some hidden camera function in my eyes.
<br>&emsp;———— a contact lens that I could just put in or a digital censor
inside the actual eyeball, updating the camera obscura we’re born with to a
mirrorless dslr. I hope it comes with vsco filters.like that’s some cyborg
shit. <br>&emsp;———— stealthier than those zooming glasses in the spy kids 2 movie that were a meme at some point. I would
maybe have to touch my temple, blink, or just think about taking a photo.
<br>&emsp;———— but then I immeadiately unwished that because it’s scary when
technology is hidden and smooth and in this case, turning anyone into a
walking spy camera. even more so than we are now with our smartphones. what
kind of imagery and surveillance would this cyborg eye help create?
<br>&emsp;———— not to focus solely on the possible evils of technological
advance, but we might end up not giving a second thought about the dangers of
increasingly invasive technology and just go on with our daily lives because
everything is so seamless and smooth. wouldn’t you as a user/consumer/person
want that? <br>&emsp;———— to feel one. no funny stuff, just an oven that you
can set to pre-heat through a mobile app while you’re on your way home with
the frozen store-bought pizza. we might hold the forbidden fruit in our hand,
so close to us, without any idea of what’s going on under the gorilla glass.
it’s always for some greater good, too, like the betterment of society, but history
is often a lot more sinister. <br>&emsp;———— it’s time to break the spell.
what happens when you gut-punch the magician?	</p>
